Reason through the theoretical and practical limits of static analysis for CI/CD pipeline security. A CICD pipeline definition (GitHub Actions workflow, GitLab CI YAML, Jenkinsfile, Azure Pipelines YAML) is a program that runs other programs. Static analysis of the pipeline file can detect structural issues — unpinned action references, missing permissions scoping, hardcoded secrets, privileged runner usage — but it fundamentally cannot reason about the behavior of the programs the pipeline invokes.

Consider the halting-problem-adjacent difficulty: a pipeline step that runs a shell script fetched from a URL cannot be statically validated for what the script does. A pipeline that uses a third-party GitHub Action pinned to a SHA is protected against tag mutation but not against the action repository being compromised and a malicious commit being added before the SHA was pinned. The GitHub Actions permission model (permissions: read-all default vs explicit grants) can be checked statically, but whether a particular permission is actually needed depends on what the workflow does at runtime.

What are the theoretical limits of static analysis for pipeline security? Formalize what classes of vulnerabilities ARE detectable via static analysis of pipeline YAML versus what classes require: dynamic analysis (actually running the pipeline in a sandbox), dependency graph analysis (understanding what each referenced action does), or human review.

How does this analysis inform the design of a pipeline generator that aims to produce maximally secure output? If certain security properties cannot be statically guaranteed, what compensating controls should be generated instead (e.g., OIDC-based short-lived credentials instead of long-lived secrets, because the credential scope can be expressed in the pipeline YAML even if the credential itself cannot be validated)?
